******
[1] China, 23rd case (Fujian), clinical features
Date: Fri 2 Mar 2007
From: Robert Yang <yang@isid.org>
Source: Xinhua News Agency [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-03/02/content_5793369.htm>

The woman farmer who was confirmed on Tuesday [27 Feb 2007] to be infected
with the deadly H5N1 strain of bird flu is in critical but stable condition
in hospital. The 44 year old woman is receiving medical treatment in
Jian'ou City Hospital, said Xu Longshan, chief of the Fujian Provincial
Professional Panel for Prevention and Control of Human Infection of Bird
Flu, on Fri 2 Mar 2007. [The patient's] pneumonia symptoms developed
quickly and she went into a coma after being admitted to hospital. A chest
x-ray on 25 Feb 2007 showed large shadows on her lungs.
According to Xu, medical experts have worked out a detailed treatment plan
to save her. As of Thursday evening [1 Mar 2007], her body temperature and
pulse had returned to normal, and her lungs and breathing appeared to be
functioning better. Doctors say the woman is still in critical situation,
however, and they are trying to boost her immunity to prevent further
organic infection. This is the country's 1st human case of bird flu in 7
weeks since China reported on 10 Jan 2007 that a 37 year old farmer in east
China's Anhui Province had contracted bird flu last December [2006] but had
recovered [see report below].
[The patient] is a native of Damiao Village, a marketplace in the
mountainous township of Xiaosong. The farmer, who keeps 5 chickens at her
home, developed symptoms including fever and pneumonia on 18 Feb 2007, and
was confirmed to be infected with the virus by the Chinese Center for
Disease Control and Prevention on 27 Feb 2007. [She] is known to have been
in contact with dead poultry.
All live poultry in Damiao Village and its adjacent areas within a 3 km
radius have been culled, and [the victim's] home and adjacent areas have
been properly disinfected, said a local government spokesman. Local markets
for live fowls and processed fowl products in Damiao and its adjacent
regions have been closed until further notice. Local health authorities
said they were closely monitoring people who had had close contacts with
[the patient]. So far, they have showed no symptoms of the disease, they said.
According to the Fujian health authorities, China's Health Ministry has
passed on the information to the World Health Organization, health agencies
in Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan province, and other countries. The virus has
killed 14 people in China since 2003.
--
